00:49:15.520 --> 00:49:24.239
you started? No, but that's, on a meta level, that was one of my biggest realizations of writing the

00:49:24.239 --> 00:49:30.560
first book. You see, I thought I knew a little bit about the Unix command line. I'll get to

00:49:30.560 --> 00:49:35.679
the Polars book in a moment, but I thought I knew about this. But as I wrote this, I was like,

00:49:35.679 --> 00:49:42.719
oh, wow, there is so much to learn here. And of course, feeling like an imposter all the while,

00:49:43.840 --> 00:49:50.000
you know, after a while, I started to realize, like, hey, you don't have to know everything

00:49:50.560 --> 00:49:56.639
in order to write a book. In fact, I would argue it's even better not to learn,

00:49:56.639 --> 00:50:01.760
not to know a whole lot about the thing you're writing about. So I discussed this with Richie

00:50:01.760 --> 00:50:09.679
Fink, the creator of Polars, and we both agree that he would probably not be the best person

00:50:09.679 --> 00:50:14.639
to write a book because he's so deep into it, right? And of course, he wants to just focus

